<section id="summary">
  <h2 class="section-title"><span class="num">01</span>Executive Summary</h2>
  <p>The global aviation industry has completed a full V-shaped recovery from the COVID-19 shock and is now compounding
  growth from a larger, more concentrated, and more capacity-disciplined base than it had in 2019. Industry revenue
  reached <b>$660.7B in 2025</b>, <b>27% above the 2019 pre-pandemic peak</b>, while average operating margin has
  stabilized around <b>8.8%</b>. Beneath this headline recovery, five structural shifts stand out: a widening
  low-cost/regional margin premium over legacy carriers, a fleet-order backlog now stretching 7–9 years at current
  delivery rates, Airbus's growing lead over Boeing, the emergence of COMAC as a credible third narrowbody OEM, and a
  clear reallocation of growth toward Middle East and Africa-linked long-haul hub routes. This report synthesizes
  those patterns into ten data-backed insights and ten candidate strategic initiatives for the coming year.</p>

  <div class="kpi-row">
    <div class="kpi"><div class="val">$660.7B</div><div class="lbl">2025 industry revenue (+27% vs 2019)</div></div>
    <div class="kpi"><div class="val">8.8%</div><div class="lbl">2025 avg. operating margin</div></div>
    <div class="kpi"><div class="val">1,219M</div><div class="lbl">2025 passengers carried</div></div>
    <div class="kpi"><div class="val">7–9 yrs</div><div class="lbl">Airbus/Boeing forward order backlog</div></div>
  </div>
</section>

