<section id="insights">
  <h2 class="section-title"><span class="num">03</span>Top 10 Insights</h2>

  <div class="insight-card">
    <span class="badge">Insight 1</span>
    <h4>The industry didn't just recover from COVID — it re-based to a higher growth trajectory</h4>
    <p>Revenue fell from $519B (2019) to $204B (2020), a <b>-60.6% collapse</b>, with average operating margin cratering
    to <b>-35.1%</b>. Revenue didn't regain 2019 levels until 2023 ($585B), and by 2025 stood at <b>$660.7B — 27.3%
    above 2019</b>. The 2022–2025 revenue CAGR is roughly <b>11.5%</b>, well above the 2010–2019 CAGR of ~5.6%.</p>
    <div class="chart-wrap"><canvas id="chart1"></canvas><div class="cap">Industry revenue ($B) and average operating margin (%), 2010–2025</div></div>
  </div>

  <div class="insight-card">
    <span class="badge">Insight 2</span>
    <h4>Low-cost and regional carriers hold a durable margin and load-factor premium over legacy</h4>
    <p>Averaged over 2023–2025: low-cost carriers posted <b>11.7% margin / 87.2% load factor</b>, regional
    <b>11.0% / 88.3%</b>, versus legacy at just <b>8.0% / 83.0%</b>. Low-cost has out-earned legacy in nearly every
    year on record, including a smaller relative loss in 2020–2021.</p>
    <div class="chart-wrap"><canvas id="chart2"></canvas><div class="cap">Operating margin (%) by business model, 2010–2025</div></div>
  </div>

  <div class="insight-card">
    <span class="badge">Insight 3</span>
    <h4>Airlines defended load factor through capacity cuts, recovering utilization years before volume</h4>
    <p>Europe's load factor collapsed to <b>55.0%</b> for eight straight months in 2020, then rebounded to
    <b>80–88%</b> throughout 2021 — near 2019 levels — even as RPK volumes stayed roughly half of 2019. Airlines cut
    capacity faster than demand fell, protecting unit economics.</p>
    <div class="chart-wrap"><canvas id="chart3"></canvas><div class="cap">Europe monthly load factor (%) vs. RPK (billions), 2019–2022</div></div>
  </div>

  <div class="insight-card">
    <span class="badge">Insight 4</span>
    <h4>The OEM order backlog has become a structural bottleneck, not a demand signal</h4>
    <p>Airbus backlog grew from 8,728 (2023) to <b>10,305 units (2025)</b>; Boeing from 6,455 to <b>7,276</b>. At
    current delivery rates, both OEMs are effectively <b>sold out 7–9 years forward</b> — fleet planning, not order
    placement, is now airlines' real constraint.</p>
    <div class="chart-wrap"><canvas id="chart4"></canvas><div class="cap">OEM backlog (units), 2023–2025, by manufacturer</div></div>
  </div>

  <div class="insight-card">
    <span class="badge">Insight 5</span>
    <h4>Airbus has pulled decisively ahead of Boeing in net orders and backlog since 2010</h4>
    <p>Over 2010–2025, Airbus logged <b>18,157 net orders</b> and a <b>108,156-unit backlog</b> vs. Boeing's
    <b>12,519 net orders</b> and <b>87,265 backlog</b> — roughly a <b>45% net-order advantage</b> for Airbus, widening
    after 2018-2019.</p>
    <div class="two-col">
      <div class="chart-wrap"><canvas id="chart5a"></canvas><div class="cap">Net orders 2010–2025 (cumulative)</div></div>
      <div class="chart-wrap"><canvas id="chart5b"></canvas><div class="cap">Backlog, end of 2025 (units)</div></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="insight-card">
    <span class="badge">Insight 6</span>
    <h4>COMAC's C919 has crossed from prototype to serial production</h4>
    <p>C919 gross orders jumped from 24 (2018) to a peak of 250 (2023). Deliveries began in 2023 (4 units) and reached
    <b>25 in 2025</b>, taking the backlog to <b>1,612 units</b> — ahead of Embraer's total accumulated backlog
    contribution of 3,194 built up over 16 years from a much larger program.</p>
    <div class="chart-wrap"><canvas id="chart6"></canvas><div class="cap">COMAC C919 backlog (units) and annual deliveries, 2018–2026</div></div>
  </div>

  <div class="insight-card">
    <span class="badge">Insight 7</span>
    <h4>Boeing aircraft are disproportionately represented in the incident record</h4>
    <p>Of 40 logged incidents, <b>22 (55%) involved Boeing</b> aircraft versus <b>8 (20%) Airbus</b>, including the
    bulk of fatal crashes. This reflects Boeing's large in-service fleet as well as 737 MAX-era events, and is a
    reputational and fleet-mix data point already being priced in by regulators and insurers.</p>
    <div class="chart-wrap" style="max-width:420px;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;"><canvas id="chart7"></canvas><div class="cap">Incident count by manufacturer (of 40 total)</div></div>
  </div>

  <div class="insight-card">
    <span class="badge">Insight 8</span>
    <h4>Geopolitical risk is concentrated but severe when it hits</h4>
    <p>Only 3 of 40 incidents (7.5%) were tagged geopolitical — aircraft shot down over conflict zones, drone attacks
    on aviation infrastructure — but these carry outsized fatality and route-disruption impact. Combined with strong
    growth on Gulf-Africa-Europe corridors, airspace-risk planning remains a live, if infrequent, tail risk.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="insight-card">
    <span class="badge">Insight 9</span>
    <h4>Middle East is the fastest-growing region on both traffic and airline-revenue measures</h4>
    <p>Middle East RPK grew <b>+66.1%</b> from 2019 to 2025 — fastest of any region — while Africa's smaller base grew
    <b>+58.5%</b>. Qatar Airways revenue grew from $9.95B (2015) to <b>$23.92B (2025), +140%</b>, and new entrant
    Riyadh Air already shows <b>$1.49B</b> in 2025 revenue.</p>
    <div class="chart-wrap"><canvas id="chart9"></canvas><div class="cap">RPK growth by region, 2019 → 2025 (%)</div></div>
  </div>

  <div class="insight-card">
    <span class="badge">Insight 10</span>
    <h4>Route economics increasingly favor yield over volume; short-haul intra-region routes have stalled</h4>
    <p>The top 10 routes by 2025 revenue are dominated by long-haul, high-fare connections (Hong Kong–San Francisco
    at $543 avg. fare, Amsterdam–Bangkok at $478) rather than the highest-volume routes. Meanwhile London–Paris
    passengers are <b>down 3.4%</b> since 2019, and São Paulo–Rio <b>down 1.7%</b>, while Gulf-hub long-haul routes
    grew 15–24% over the same period.</p>
    <div class="chart-wrap"><canvas id="chart10"></canvas><div class="cap">Passenger growth 2019→2025 (%): fastest-growing vs. stalled routes</div></div>
  </div>

</section>

<section id="projects">
  <h2 class="section-title"><span class="num">04</span>Top 10 Strategic Projects for Next Year</h2>
  <ol class="projects-list">
    <li><b>High-yield long-haul network expansion</b> — prioritize capacity and codeshare/JV agreements on Gulf-, Africa-, and Asia-Pacific-linked hub routes, the fastest-growing and highest-revenue segments (Insights 9–10).</li>
    <li><b>Legacy-to-low-cost margin closing program</b> — deploy ancillary revenue, dynamic pricing, and load-factor practices proven by low-cost/regional carriers (Insight 2) across legacy hub operations.</li>
    <li><b>Fleet delivery-slot &amp; backlog risk office</b> — manage the 7–9 year OEM backlog (Insight 4): secure/resell delivery positions, extend leases, build bridging MRO capacity.</li>
    <li><b>OEM diversification / COMAC evaluation program</b> — commission a technical and commercial assessment of the C919 as a narrowbody hedge (Insight 6) against Airbus/Boeing lead times.</li>
    <li><b>Capacity-discipline analytics platform</b> — institutionalize the ASK/RPK matching discipline that protected load factor in 2020–2021 (Insight 3) as a standing network-planning capability.</li>
    <li><b>Fleet-mix and safety-reputation risk review</b> — given the Boeing-weighted incident record (Insight 7), reassess fleet-type exposure, insurance terms, and customer safety communications.</li>
    <li><b>Geopolitical route-resilience &amp; airspace risk framework</b> — build standing monitoring and rapid-rerouting capability for conflict-zone airspace (Insight 8).</li>
    <li><b>Middle East / Africa market entry or partnership review</b> — evaluate equity, codeshare, or JV opportunities with high-growth Gulf carriers (Insight 9), including new entrants like Riyadh Air.</li>
    <li><b>Short-haul network rationalization</b> — reassess capacity on stalled short-haul routes (Insight 10); redeploy aircraft/slots toward growing long-haul corridors.</li>
    <li><b>Next-shock financial resilience stress test</b> — using the 2020 margin collapse (-35pp) as the stress scenario, refresh liquidity and capacity-ramp playbooks.</li>
  </ol>
</section>

